# {{project-name | title_case}}

A jackdaw game generated from the
[jackdaw-template-game](https://github.com/jbuehler23/jackdaw_template_game)
template.

## Build

1. Open jackdaw.
2. Click **File → Extensions → Build from project folder…** and
   select this project's root directory. Jackdaw runs `cargo build`
   with `RUSTC_WRAPPER=jackdaw-rustc-wrapper` so the produced
   cdylib shares bevy types with the editor. The built `.so` is
   installed to `~/.config/jackdaw/games/` (platform-specific —
   separate from `~/.config/jackdaw/extensions/`).

## First run: restart jackdaw

Games have to register their systems against jackdaw's `App` at
startup, so after the first build you need to restart jackdaw.
On the next launch the loader picks the game up from
`~/.config/jackdaw/games/` and wires in `GamePlugin::build`.
Future versions will skip this restart via a snapshot-and-respawn
flow.

## Play

1. Click the **Play** button in the top-right toolbar. A spinning
   cube appears.
2. **Pause** freezes time. **Play** again resumes. **Stop**
   restores the scene to its pre-Play state (game-spawned
   entities disappear, the authored scene comes back).

## Editing

Put your game systems inside `GamePlugin::build` in
`src/lib.rs`. Attach `.run_if(in_state(PlayState::Playing))` to
each system so it only runs while Play is engaged.

While the game is running you can click an entity in the
hierarchy and edit its components. The game's systems see your
changes next frame.

## Rebuild

Edit the code, save, click **Build from project folder…** again.
Same restart-to-play caveat applies until the snapshot-and-respawn
flow ships.

## Why the first build is slow

The first `cargo build` compiles all of bevy from crates.io —
~500 crates, a few minutes on most machines. The resulting
`libbevy-<hash>.rlib` is never actually linked; jackdaw's rustc
wrapper redirects `--extern bevy=` at the editor's
`libjackdaw_sdk.so` so TypeIds match across the FFI boundary.
Subsequent edits to your own code rebuild in seconds.
